=========================================
🔥 Exception Handling in C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================

1. What is Exception Handling?
------------------------------
- Mechanism to handle runtime errors safely.
- Prevents program from crashing unexpectedly.
- Uses:
    try   → block where error may occur
    throw → signal an error
    catch → handle the error

-----------------------------------------
2. Basic Syntax
-----------------------------------------

try {
    // risky code
    throw exception;
}
catch (type e) {
    // handle error
}
catch (...) {
    // catch all handler
}

-----------------------------------------
3. Example
-----------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    try {
        int a = 10, b = 0;

        if (b == 0)
            throw "Division by zero error";

        cout << a / b;
    }
    catch (const char* msg) {
        cout << "Error: " << msg << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

-----------------------------------------
4. throw keyword
-----------------------------------------
- Used to explicitly raise an exception.
- Can throw:
    * primitive types (int, char, string)
    * objects
    * custom exception classes

Example:
throw 404;
throw "Error";
throw MyException();

-----------------------------------------
5. Stack Unwinding (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------
- When exception is thrown:
    → function calls are reversed
    → objects in stack are destroyed automatically

Example flow:

main()
 └── func1()
      └── func2()  → throw error
           ↑ stack unwinding starts here

Key Points:
- Local objects are destroyed automatically
- Destructors are called in reverse order
- Heap memory is NOT freed automatically (use smart pointers)

-----------------------------------------
6. Custom Exceptions
-----------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MyException {
public:
    string msg;
    MyException(string m) : msg(m) {}
};

int main() {
    try {
        throw MyException("Custom error occurred");
    }
    catch (MyException e) {
        cout << e.msg << endl;
    }
}

-----------------------------------------
7. catch(...) (Catch-all handler)
-----------------------------------------

try {
    throw 10;
}
catch (...) {
    cout << "Unknown error occurred";
}

-----------------------------------------
8. noexcept (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------
- Guarantees function will NOT throw exceptions.

Syntax:
void func() noexcept;

Example:

void safeFunc() noexcept {
    cout << "No exceptions here";
}

-----------------------------------------
9. Why noexcept is important?
-----------------------------------------
- Enables compiler optimizations
- Used heavily in STL (vector, move semantics)
- If noexcept function throws → std::terminate() is called

-----------------------------------------
10. noexcept + STL relation
-----------------------------------------
- STL prefers noexcept move constructors
- If move constructor is NOT noexcept → copy is used instead of move
- Improves performance and safety in containers

-----------------------------------------
🔥 INTERVIEW SUMMARY
-----------------------------------------
✔ try / catch / throw are core mechanism
✔ Stack unwinding ensures safe cleanup
✔ Prefer RAII / smart pointers for memory safety
✔ Custom exceptions improve design clarity
✔ noexcept improves performance & STL optimization
✔ catch(...) is last safety net
